  "title": "",
  "body": "The paper Outbreak of 2009 Pandemic Influenza A (H1N1) at a New York City School describes a high school outbreak from April 2009. The article appears in the New England Journal of Medicine in Volume 361, published in 2009, pages 2628-2636. The authors are Justin Lessler, Nicholas G. Reich, Derek A.T. Cummings, and the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene Swine Influenza Investigation Team. Here is a link to the article: https:\/\/www.nejm.org\/doi\/full\/10.1056\/NEJMoa0906089. Data from the outbreak, along with 2-day prevalence data computed as in , appear in . We use only two days for prevalence because people with flu symptoms typically stay home. This model, therefore, supposes they may go to school briefly while feeling sick, but then they stay home and no longer spread the illness to others at the school.  H1N1 Influenza Data from a New York City High School, 2009    Date (Day)  New Cases  2-day Prevalence    April 18 (Day 0)  23  23    April 19 (Day 1)  10  33    April 20 (Day 2)  17  50    April 21 (Day 3)  23  73    April 22 (Day 4)  103  176    April 23 (Day 5)  267  420    April 24 (Day 6)  147  557    April 25 (Day 7)  100  640    April 26 (Day 8)  50  667    April 27 (Day 9)  17  581    April 28 (Day 10)  7  321    April 29 (Day 11)  7  181    April 30 (Day 12)  7  88    May 1 (Day 13)  3  41      Use Python to plot the 2-day prevalence data.    Construct an SIR model with parameter values for this outbreak, where the compartment recognizes that people self-isolate by not going to school for some of the time when they are Infectious. Use in your model the information that the population is 2934 people (students plus employees) and the infectious period was 2 days (to match the 2-day prevalence assumption). Implement an RSS approach to select a preferred value of .  Include your Python code, and show at least three different values of that you tried, along with the corresponding RSS value for each value of . Then state your selected value of and graph the 2-day prevalence Data Values on the same axes as the Model Output, that is, the graph produced by using your selected value of .    Discuss your results from part (b). Qualitatively, how well does the curve fit the Data Values when you use your selected value of ? Consider how rapidly the curve increases and decreases, and the height and timing of when the 2-day prevalence curve peaks.    The value of for H1N1 has been estimated to be between 1.4 and 1.6, and a typical length of infectiousness for H1N1 is 5 days. Using and , what value of would result from this information? How close is the value of you selected using RSS to the range of values of that make sense in ? Discuss possible reasons for the outcome you found, whether you found that the values are close or not very close. In your homework, show your Python code, and show at least three different values of that you tried, along with the corresponding RSS value for each value of . Which value of leads to the smallest RSS value?  Compare the value of you selected in part (b) with this value of computed using . They are likely different. The model in this exercise assumes a level of isolation that is not considered when using . Discuss the ways that this change, as well as other aspects of the model and outbreak in this exercise, result in a different value of .   "
